    <div class="hero-content">
      <div class="badge">Ohio Native Plant · Bottomland Wildflower</div>
      <h1>Wingstem<em>Verbesina alternifolia</em></h1>
      <p class="hero-tagline">A tall perennial of moist woods and stream bottoms, named for the leafy "wings" that run down its stem — topped in late summer by branched sprays of ragged, golden flower heads alive with bees and butterflies.</p>
      <div class="flagship-badge">✦ Winged Stems</div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="facts-band">
    <div class="fact-item"><span class="fact-label">Type</span><span class="fact-value">Native perennial</span></div>
    <div class="fact-item"><span class="fact-label">Height</span><span class="fact-value">3–8 feet</span></div>
    <div class="fact-item"><span class="fact-label">Bloom</span><span class="fact-value">Late summer to fall</span></div>
    <div class="fact-item"><span class="fact-label">Light</span><span class="fact-value">Full sun to part shade</span></div>
    <div class="fact-item"><span class="fact-label">Moisture</span><span class="fact-value">Medium to moist</span></div>
    <div class="fact-item"><span class="fact-label">Family</span><span class="fact-value">Asteraceae</span></div>
  </div>

  <!-- ABOUT -->
  <section class="section">
    <p class="eyebrow">About This Plant</p>
    <h2>The Winged Stem</h2>
    <p>Wingstem is a tall, rangy perennial named for an unusual feature you can read with a fingertip: thin, leafy ridges — "wings" — run lengthwise down the stem, formed where the bases of the alternate leaves continue downward along it. The leaves themselves are lance-shaped, tapering, and toothed; the whole plant can reach well over head height by late summer.</p>
    <p>Its flowers match its informal habit. Branched sprays at the stem tips carry many small yellow heads, each with only a few ray florets, unevenly spaced and often drooping around a domed centre — a dishevelled, "bad-hair-day" daisy that gives the plant its other common name, yellow ironweed. It grows in moist woods, floodplains, stream banks, ditches, and bottomland thickets, often forming colonies in sun to part shade.</p>

    <div class="keystone-callout">
      <p>Tall, open, and flowering late, wingstem holds its many small heads up where insects can reach them easily, making it a <strong>generous late-summer nectar and pollen source</strong> in moist, partly shaded ground where fewer composites grow. Its seeds are later taken by finches and other songbirds.</p>
    </div>

    <p class="eyebrow" style="margin-top: 1.2rem; margin-bottom: 0.4rem">Best garden uses</p>
    <div class="pill-list">
      <span class="pill">Rain gardens</span>
      <span class="pill">Moist borders</span>
      <span class="pill">Streambank plantings</span>
      <span class="pill">Pollinator gardens</span>
      <span class="pill">Part-shade meadows</span>
      <span class="pill">Naturalizing</span>
    </div>
  </section>

