  <section class="section">
    <p class="eyebrow">Seasonal Interest</p>
    <h2>A Year in the Life</h2>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="tl-row active"><div class="tl-season">Spring</div><div class="tl-bar"></div><div class="tl-text">Clumps push up from the crown, and the winged stems begin to rise — the leafy ridges along them visible early.</div></div>
      <div class="tl-row active"><div class="tl-season">Early sum.</div><div class="tl-bar"></div><div class="tl-text">Rapid, tall growth. The plant gains much of its height, the winged stems conspicuous, the flower branches forming at the top.</div></div>
      <div class="tl-row peak"><div class="tl-season">Late sum.</div><div class="tl-bar"></div><div class="tl-text">Peak bloom — open, branched sprays of ragged yellow heads open above the foliage and are worked steadily by bees and butterflies.</div></div>
      <div class="tl-row fade"><div class="tl-season">Fall</div><div class="tl-bar"></div><div class="tl-text">Flowering fades to seed; the flat, two-awned seeds ripen and are taken by goldfinches and other songbirds. The tall stems stand.</div></div>
      <div class="tl-row"><div class="tl-season">Winter</div><div class="tl-bar"></div><div class="tl-text">Dried stems and seed heads persist, the winged stems still legible in silhouette, before being cut back in late winter.</div></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <p class="eyebrow">Wildlife Support</p>
    <h2>Who Visits</h2>
    <p>Wingstem's many small, open heads, held high and blooming late, draw a broad mix of insects — native bees, bumblebees, wasps, flies, and butterflies. It is also a documented larval host for the silvery checkerspot butterfly, and supports the caterpillars of some moths, though those associations vary by place.</p>
    <div class="insect-hub">
      <div class="insect-category">
        <div class="insect-category-header"><span class="insect-category-icon">🐝</span><span class="insect-category-name">Bees &amp; Wasps</span><span class="insect-count-badge">nectar &amp; pollen</span></div>
        <div class="insect-list">
          <span class="insect-tag common">Native Bees</span>
          <span class="insect-tag">Bumblebees</span>
          <span class="insect-tag">Wasps</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="insect-category">
        <div class="insect-category-header"><span class="insect-category-icon">🦋</span><span class="insect-category-name">Butterflies &amp; Moths</span><span class="insect-count-badge">nectar + larvae</span></div>
        <div class="insect-list">
          <span class="insect-tag common">Silvery Checkerspot</span>
          <span class="insect-tag">Skippers</span>
          <span class="insect-tag">Moth Larvae</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="insect-category">
        <div class="insect-category-header"><span class="insect-category-icon">🪰</span><span class="insect-category-name">Flies &amp; Others</span><span class="insect-count-badge">nectar</span></div>
        <div class="insect-list">
          <span class="insect-tag">Flower Flies</span>
          <span class="insect-tag">Beetles</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p style="margin-top: 1.2rem;">Beyond its insect visitors, wingstem feeds birds: its <strong>ripe seed</strong> is a draw for goldfinches and other songbirds in fall, and the standing stems add winter structure to a moist planting.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <p class="eyebrow">Care &amp; Cultivation</p>
    <h2>Growing Conditions</h2>
    <p>Wingstem is easy and vigorous wherever it has moisture, taking sun or part shade and tolerating more shade than most composites. That vigour is the thing to plan for: in rich, moist ground it grows tall and spreads by both rhizome and seed, so it is best where it has room to form a colony rather than in a tidy, confined bed.</p>
    <table class="care-table">
      <tr><td>Light</td><td>Full sun to part shade; takes more shade than most daisies</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Soil</td><td>Average to rich; tolerates clay and seasonal moisture</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Moisture</td><td>Medium to moist; happiest on bottomland and stream banks</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Habit</td><td>Tall and colony-forming; spreads by rhizomes and seed — give it room</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Height</td><td>Often 5–8 ft in rich soil; site it at the back, where height is welcome</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Maintenance</td><td>Low; cut back in late winter, and divide or thin to limit spread</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Wildlife</td><td>Leave seed heads standing for finches and winter structure</td></tr>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <p class="eyebrow">Planting Partners</p>
    <h2>Grows Well With</h2>
    <p>Wingstem suits the back of a moist, sunny-to-part-shade planting — rain gardens, bottomland borders, and stream edges — among other tall, late natives that can hold their own beside it.</p>
    <div class="companion-group">
      <p class="companion-group-label">Bottomland giants</p>
      <div class="companion-list">
        <div class="companion-row"><div class="companion-dot"></div><div><span class="companion-common">Joe-Pye Weed</span> <span class="companion-latin">Eutrochium spp.</span></div></div>
        <div class="companion-row"><div class="companion-dot"></div><div><span class="companion-common">Ironweed</span> <span class="companion-latin">Vernonia spp.</span></div></div>
        <div class="companion-row"><div class="companion-dot"></div><div><span class="companion-common">Cup Plant</span> <span class="companion-latin">Silphium perfoliatum</span></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="companion-group">
      <p class="companion-group-label">Moist-meadow company</p>
      <div class="companion-list">
        <div class="companion-row"><div class="companion-dot"></div><div><span class="companion-common">Boneset</span> <span class="companion-latin">Eupatorium perfoliatum</span></div></div>
        <div class="companion-row"><div class="companion-dot"></div><div><span class="companion-common">Culver's Root</span> <span class="companion-latin">Veronicastrum virginicum</span></div></div>
        <div class="companion-row"><div class="companion-dot"></div><div><span class="companion-common">Blue Vervain</span> <span class="companion-latin">Verbena hastata</span></div></div>
