  <section class="section fact-feature">
    <p class="eyebrow">Did You Know?</p>
    <h2>The Stories Behind This Plant</h2>

    <div class="story-card story-card--highlight">
      <div class="story-number">01</div>
      <div class="story-body">
        <h3 class="story-title">Wings on the Stem</h3>
        <p>Run a finger up the stem and you can feel where the name comes from: thin, leafy ridges run lengthwise along it, formed where each leaf base continues downward as a <strong>decurrent</strong> flange. These "wings" make wingstem easy to identify even when it is not in flower, and set it apart from the many other tall yellow composites of late summer.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="story-card">
      <div class="story-number">02</div>
      <div class="story-body">
        <h3 class="story-title">A Ragged Kind of Daisy</h3>
        <p>Where a sunflower or coneflower carries a tidy ring of even rays, wingstem's heads look deliberately undone — a handful of ray florets, unevenly spaced and often bent back or drooping, around a small domed disc. The effect is more wild than formal, and it is part of why the plant reads as a creature of the floodplain and ditch rather than the flower bed.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="story-card">
      <div class="story-number">03</div>
      <div class="story-body">
        <h3 class="story-title">Tall Forage, Late and Open</h3>
        <p>By blooming late and holding many accessible flowers high on open, branched stems, wingstem extends the season's forage in moist, partly shaded places where late nectar can be scarce. It draws a wide range of bees and butterflies, serves as a larval host for the silvery checkerspot, and then feeds finches on its ripe seed — a long arc of use from summer into winter.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="story-card">
      <div class="story-number">04</div>
      <div class="story-body">
        <h3 class="story-title">Wingstems &amp; Crownbeards</h3>
        <p>Wingstem belongs to the genus <em>Verbesina</em>, the crownbeards — a small group of tall, late-blooming composites. Its best-known relative, white crownbeard or "frostweed" (<em>Verbesina virginica</em>), is famous for a winter trick: as the first hard freezes arrive, sap freezing in the base of the stem splits the bark and pushes out delicate ribbons of ice, the so-called "frost flowers." The genus is the subject of the showcase below.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <p class="eyebrow">Genus Verbesina</p>
    <h2>Meet the Crownbeards</h2>
    <p><em>Verbesina</em> — the wingstems and crownbeards — is a small genus of tall, late-blooming natives, several with winged stems like this one. Wingstem is the common Ohio member, of moist woods and bottomland; its relatives are scarcer here or belong farther south, and sort out by flower colour and habitat.</p>
    <div class="species-grid">
      <div class="species-card featured">
        <p class="species-tag">Most Common · Garden-Ready</p>
        <p class="species-common">Wingstem</p>
        <p class="species-latin">Verbesina alternifolia</p>
        <p class="species-desc">The species profiled on this page: winged stems, alternate toothed leaves, and branched sprays of ragged yellow heads in late summer. The common crownbeard of Ohio's moist woods, floodplains, and stream bottoms.</p>
        <div class="species-traits"><span class="species-trait">3–8 ft</span><span class="species-trait">Moist · part shade</span><span class="species-trait">Yellow</span><span class="species-trait">Winged stem</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="species-card">
        <p class="species-tag">Dry prairie &amp; open woods</p>
        <p class="species-common">Yellow Crownbeard</p>
        <p class="species-latin">Verbesina helianthoides</p>
        <p class="species-desc">A shorter, more sunflower-like species of dry prairies and open woods, with winged stems and fuller, neater yellow heads. Uncommon in Ohio, on drier ground than wingstem.</p>
        <div class="species-traits"><span class="species-trait">2–4 ft</span><span class="species-trait">Dry–medium</span><span class="species-trait">Yellow</span><span class="species-trait">Winged stem</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="species-card">
        <p class="species-tag">White-flowered · Frost flowers</p>
        <p class="species-common">White Crownbeard</p>
        <p class="species-latin">Verbesina virginica</p>
        <p class="species-desc">"Frostweed" — a white-flowered crownbeard of woodland edges and bottoms, mostly south of Ohio, known for the ribbons of ice its stems extrude at the first hard freezes.</p>
        <div class="species-traits"><span class="species-trait">3–6 ft</span><span class="species-trait">Med–moist</span><span class="species-trait">White</span><span class="species-trait">Frost flowers</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="species-card">
        <p class="species-tag">Southern · Clearings</p>
        <p class="species-common">Southern Crownbeard</p>
        <p class="species-latin">Verbesina occidentalis</p>
        <p class="species-desc">A taller, more weedy crownbeard of clearings, roadsides, and old fields to the south, with sparse, few-rayed yellow heads. Largely outside Ohio, included here to round out the genus.</p>
        <div class="species-traits"><span class="species-trait">3–6 ft</span><span class="species-trait">Medium</span><span class="species-trait">Yellow</span><span class="species-trait">Sparse rays</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

